{{Infobox person | name = Pavel Feoktistovich Chernyshev | image = | caption = | birth_date = sometime in/around 1854 | birth_place = [[Samara Oblast|Samara]] province, [[Russian Empire|Empire of Russia]] | education = Medical and Surgical Academy, St. Petersburg | alma_mater = | home_town = | residence = | parents = | occupation = Medical student | years_active = | death_date = March 1876 | death_place = [[St. Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Empire of Russia]] | party = Narodnik (Populist)<ref name="gse"/> | spouse = | children = | family = }}
==Birth and class==
Pavel Feoktistovich Chernyshev was born around 1854 in [[Samara Oblast|Samara]], in the [[Empire of Russia]], to noble parents.<ref name="gse">Pavel Feoktistovich Chernyshev entry, [[The Great Soviet Encyclopedia]], 1979. [http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Pavel+Chernyshev]</ref>
==Life and death==
By 1874, Chernyshev was a medical student at the Medical and Surgical Academy in [[St. Petersburg]]. While a student, he helped organize and served as treasurer for the Samartsy, a [[populist]] St. Petersburg student society.<ref name="gse"/> He took part in the "Going to the People" movement, and it is for this participation that he was arrested by authorities on August 30, 1874 and incarcerated shortly thereafter. He was released on bail on March 11, 1876; having contracted [[tuberculosis]] while in prison, he died in a hospital soon after his release.<ref name="gse"/>
Chernyshev's primary claims to fame are his imprisonment, death, and funeral, all of which occurred over about 18 months from his arrest to his funeral on March 30, 1876. The funeral at [[Volkovo Cemetery]] became the seed of a large populist anti-government demonstration,<ref>"Rites of Protest: Populist Funerals in Imperial St. Petersburg, 1876-1878" [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2697643?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents]</ref> and the composer [[Grigori A. Machtet]] wrote the poem "The Last Farewell" (literally "Succumbed to the ordeal of imprisonment") in his memory. The poem lives on as the lyrics to the song "Slavery and Suffering," (''Esclavage et souffrance'')<ref name="youtube">"Esclavage et souffrance." Performed by Alexandrov Ensemble, (former) Red Army Choir. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4eA1IkCGEtM</ref> which has been performed by the [[Alexandrov Ensemble|Red Army Choir]] and was a popular revolutionary song.
==References== {{Reflist}}
