In November 2015 the [[Chickasaw Nation]], through the Chickasaw Language Revitalization Program established in 2007, contracted with Rosetta Stone to customize language learning content to preserve and introduce the [[Chickasaw language]] to its 60,000+ members worldwide.<ref>Davis, J. (2016). Language affiliation and ethnolinguistic identity in chickasaw language revitalization. Language & Communication, 47, 100-111. doi:10.1016/j.langcom.2015.04.005</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://investors.rosettastone.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=227935&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=2107339|title=Press  Release - Investor Relations - Rosetta Stone|publisher=|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>  This effort comes as the Chickasaw Nation has approximately 50 native speakers remaining, with its last monolingual speaker having died in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2014/01/07/260555554/what-happens-when-a-languages-last-monolingual-speaker-dies|title=What Happens When A Language's Last Monolingual Speaker Dies?|publisher=|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>

==Reception and efficacy==

===Critiques from language experts===
Frequent criticism of the program arises in its lack of sensitivity to the differences between the various languages it comes in and their respective cultures.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Shaughnessy|first=Michael|title=CALL, commercialism and culture: inherent software design conflicts and their results|journal=ReCALL|year=2003|volume=15|issue=2|pages=251–268|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=214455}}</ref> Early versions of the software presented the same concepts in the same order, using the same images taken mostly in the [[Washington, D.C.]] area near the company's headquarters at the time in [[Harrisonburg, Virginia|Harrisonburg]], [[Virginia]]. In the most recent version, there have been some modifications to the picture set for certain languages or regions.

Another frequent issue was the use of more formal vocabulary than that regularly used by native speakers. In 2006, ''[[Macworld]]'' reviewer Cyrus Farivar noted that his Persian CD used ''khodrow'' for "car", although most native speakers use a [[List of French loanwords in Persian|French loanword]], ''ma:sheen''. The same course did not teach words that would be important to someone learning [[Persian language|Persian]], such as "bread" and "tea"; however, it very curiously included the word "elephant" in a basic vocabulary lesson. Perplexed by the question of why the word "elephant" would be taught in a language where it might never be used (there are not many elephants in Iran), Farivar called Rosetta Stone, Inc. He was told that the company makes four different picture sets: one for Western languages, another for Asian languages, and two sets unique to each [[Swahili language|Swahili]] and [[Latin]]. The [[Persian language|Persian]] language CD was using the Western picture set, which explains why the images were not culturally relevant.<ref name="Macworld 2006 review">Farivar, Cyrus; January 19, 2006; [http://www.macworld.com/2006/01/reviews/rosettastone3/index.php Foreign-language software provides a comprehensive approach to learning]; ''[[Macworld]]'', retrieved July 12, 2006</ref>

====Donald McRae on the German course====
Writing in 1997, Donald McRae of [[Brock University]] said that Rosetta Stone represented "good pedagogy" and that "the authors of the program never lose sight of solid teaching methodology". He described the Version 2 German language course as "very good", but indicated that he had "some reservations".{{explain|date=January 2013}}<ref name="McRae">McRae, Donald; June 24, 1997; [http://www-writing.berkeley.edu/chorus/call/reviews/archives/rosettagerm.html Review: The Rosetta Stone for German]; CALL @Chorus; retrieved October 22, 2006.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205014752/http://www-writing.berkeley.edu/chorus/call/reviews/archives/rosettagerm.html |date=December 5, 2006 }}</ref>

====Mark Kaiser on the Russian course====
In a 1997 review of the Version 2 Russian language course, Mark Kaiser, director of the Language Media Center at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], called the program "woefully inadequate for a number of reasons".<ref name="Kaiser">Kaiser, Mark; September 25, 1997; [http://www-writing.berkeley.edu/chorus/call/reviews/rosetta_russian/index.html Review: The Rosetta Stone for Russian], CALL @Chorus, retrieved October 22, 2006.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060913073027/http://www-writing.berkeley.edu/chorus/call/reviews/rosetta_russian/index.html |date=September 13, 2006 }}</ref>

One of Kaiser's observations was that Rosetta Stone software fails to provide a relevant cultural context. Because the company uses the same [[stock photograph]]s for all its language courses, they depict people, activities, and manufactured goods that are conspicuously American. Kaiser also found that Rosetta Stone Version 2 does not provide a way for students to evaluate their conversation skills, and that some of the words and phrases are too English-based.

"The entire package lacks any [[Language pedagogy|pedagogical]] foundation," he concluded. "Rather, it utilizes the glitz of the [[Multimedia computer|multimedia]] capabilities of the computer, a dearth of quality foreign language software, and clever marketing to create an economically successful product."<ref name="Kaiser" />{{Dead link|date=January 2012}}

Brendan Lewis, a world traveler, made similar observations in his critique nearly 14 years later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fluentin3months.com/rosetta-stone-review/ |title=Review of Rosetta Stone: Detailed and honest look at latest version (TOTALe) |last=Lewis |first=Brendan |work=Fluent in 3 Months |accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref>

====Stephen Krashen's Review====

The language-learning specialist Stephen Krashen found that the few studies on the software produced learning results that were "about as effective as traditional instruction on traditional tests."<ref>Krashen, Stephen, 2013, "Rosetta Stone:  Does Not Provide Compelling Input, Research Reports at Best Suggestive, Conflicting Reports on Users' Attitudes," ''The International Journal of Foreign Language Teaching'', April 2013, pp. 1-4; quotation from p. 4.  
http://www.tprstories.com/images/ijflt/articles-april-2013/Krashen-Rosetta-Stone.pdf</ref>

===End User License Agreement===
The user purchases a licence to use the software, which is non-transferable. Up to five members of a household may use a single licence.<ref>http://resources.rosettastone.com/CDN/global/pdfs/Global-EULA.pdf</ref>

